   lea (%rdx,%rcx,8),%rcx<br />&gt;&gt; 12:   movl %ecx,%edx          /* ecx is zerorest also */<br />&gt;<br />&gt; -&gt; Even if %rdx+%rcx*8 &gt; 2^32 we end up truncating at 12: -- not that it<br />&gt; matters, since both arguments are prototyped as "unsigned" and therefore<br />&gt; the C compiler is supposed to guarantee the upper 32 bits are ignored.<br /><br />Ahh. That was the one I thought was broken, but yes, while the upper<br />bits of %rcx are calculated and not zeroed, they end up not actually<br />getting used. So yeah, I'll believe it's correct.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
